Managers




1000
IT employees




$1.3BEST.
IT Budget




American Airlines Group was formed by the merger of AMR Corporation (AMR) and US Airways in December 2013.  The company operates throughout the United States, Canada, Latin America, the Caribbean, Western Europe, Japan, China, and India.

American Airlines discontinued the US… MoreAmerican Airlines Group was formed by the merger of AMR Corporation (AMR) and US Airways in December 2013.  The company operates throughout the United States, Canada, Latin America, the Caribbean, Western Europe, Japan, China, and India.

American Airlines discontinued the US Airways in 2015.  The company is continuing to work to integrate following its merger in 2013.
American Airlines Group was formed by the merger of AMR Corporation (AMR) and US Airways in December 2013.  The company operates through its principal subsidiaries, American Airlines, Inc. and US Airways.  The company operates throughout the United States, Canada, Latin… MoreAmerican Airlines Group was formed by the merger of AMR Corporation (AMR) and US Airways in December 2013.  The company operates through its principal subsidiaries, American Airlines, Inc. and US Airways.  The company operates throughout the United States, Canada, Latin America, the Caribbean, Western Europe, Japan, China, and India.

IT Priorities:
• The American Airlines parent company AMR Corp. has merged with US Airways to form the new American Airlines Group. While the company will maintain divided services, a systems integration is underway and is expected to be completed by mid-2015.
• Focused on cloud to handle scalability, not for budget cutting purposes. 
• Pursuing mobility initiatives on the spending priorities include porting legacy applications onto new devices, enterprise mobile application development, mobilizing internally deployed applications, updating legacy mobile applications and bring your own device (BYOD). 
• Experiencing pain surrounding identity and access management following a couple of data breaches. 
• Developing applications that help provide passenger solutions, reservations, and employee travel and benefits. Additional applications specialists help develop flight training simulators to train future pilots.
• Upgrading and maintaining SAP environment. 
• Maintaining payment card identity (PCI) compliance. 

IT Structure:
• Due to the merging of the two airlines, realignment will occur at the director and manager level.  
• Approximately 800 technical support staff are contract workers.

IT Vendors:
• EDS is the main technical support provider, but IBM also provides services in human resources. 

IT Intelligence Snippets
2013:
• Less than 30% of IT staff is dedicated to the sustenance of its ERP platform.
• Lost access to a key computer system, causing almost 2000 flight delays and cancellations. 
• The IT budget is typically finalized in Q4.
• Increasing spending in remote access control, communication systems, wide area networking (WAN)/local area networking (LAN)/VPN, and network devices, and decrease spending in network security. 
• Utilizes public and private cloud services from Amazon and Microsoft.

2012:
• Significant spending increase in security management and internal security, and slight spending increases in mobile device security, encryption, and perimeter security. 
• Completed an IBM Informix database upgrade in the early part of 2012.
• Implemented the use of approximately 1,000 mobile device on their airlines. The devices will be linked up to a small cloud based server, much like Netflix, where customers will have the ability to view and stream media during the flight.





